f=\"http://cdn.yougov.com/cumulus_uploads/document/zinooici1f/YG-Archive-Pol-Sunday-Times-results-120713.pdf\" title=\"\">reported again</a> on Monday, the day of the national roll-out of the benefits cap, the idea of limiting the maximum amount of benefits a family can receive so that they don't get more than a similar family on the average wage – about £500 a week – is extremely popular, with a 79% approval rating. Part of that must be down to the way the language of welfare reform is surreptitiously laced with innuendo about scroungers and skivers. Being popular, though, is a long, long way from being right. And when Iain Duncan Smith, the work and pensions secretary, justifies his policy with unsupported assertions and dodgy statistics, Liam Byrne, his Labour shadow, ought to have a smarter response in mind than appearing to try to sound tougher still – as he did on Monday with his attack on Tory competence.</p><p>This is not to underestimate Labour's <a href=\"http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2013/06/05/margin-calls/\" title=\"\">difficulties</a>. The Tory strategy of eliding its undeserving benefits claimants narrative with Labour's traditional concern for the poor – in his Today programme interview, Mr Duncan Smith repeatedly referred to Labour as \"the welfare party\" in order to undermine its criticisms of his policy – is too slippery to address easily. Last month, after too long a delay, Ed Miliband began to counter attack. He took the key step of <a href=\"http://www.labour.org.uk/one-nation-social-security-reform-miliband-speech\" title=\"\">accepting the case for a benefit cap</a>, and he set out the kind of structural reforms that would tackle the underlying causes of benefit dependence – more jobs, cheaper childcare, lower cost housing. All of these are right and important, but as a whole the argument is too big and complex to establish in a single speech. It's like trying to divert a cruise missile by firing bits of silver paper in the air.</p><p>That's the context of Mr Byrne's accurate but <a href=\" http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/07/labours-disastrous-new-line-attack-benefit-cap-its-too-soft\" title=\"\">tactically dangerous attack</a> on Monday on Conservative incompetence. Undoubtedly, there's a certain black humour in showing that the cap won't work because ministers haven't managed to construct the system so that it does what they want it to do. But the job of the opposition is not to show the government how to do the wrong policy better; it's to explain persuasively to voters why <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/15/benefit-cap-defiance-logic-editorial\" title=\"\">it's wrong in the first place</a>. Right now, raising the issue of competence might not be such a smart move either.</p><p>Meanwhile, as thousands of families face moving out of their homes to unfamiliar areas and new schools away from family networks, the policy continues to fray. The continued <a href=\" http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2013/jul/10/universal-credit-suffers-delays\" title=\"\">delay in introducing universal credit</a> is one problem; the anticipated cost to individual local authorities of thousands more homeless families – first raised by the communities secretary Eric Pickles <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2011/jul/02/full-text-letter-eric-pickles-welfare-reform\" title=\"\">more than two years ago</a> – is another. Mr Duncan Smith still has only <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2013/jul/15/benefits-cap-rolled-out-britain\" title=\"\">questionable statistics</a> with which to defend his muddled policy objectives. On Monday – after the public reprimand earlier this year for misrepresenting findings about the impact of the benefit cap on jobseeking in the scheme's pilot areas – he produced his own department's research, based on a sample so small that no reliable conclusions about the likelihood of looking for work could be deduced. No wonder he has to rely on gut instinct.</p>","headline":"Benefit cap: perils of gut instinct","trailText":"<strong>Editorial: </strong>Hard-pressed taxpayers are being encouraged to consider the cost of benefits as some kind of plunder","newspaperPageNumber":"32","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/7/15/1373921990030/Iain-Duncan-Smith-005.jpg","wordcount":"678","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"412890270","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"7839021","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Editorial","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-07-16T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1937146","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-07-18T20:55:23Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/15/benefit-cap-editorial","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/15/benefit-cap-editorial","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","webTitle":"Comment is free","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","references":[]},{"id":"politics/welfare","webTitle":"Welfare","type":"keyword","sectionId":"politics","sectionName":"Politics","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/welfare","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/politics/welfare","references":[]},{"id":"society/benefits","webTitle":"Benefits","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/benefits","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/society/benefits","references":[]},{"id":"society/society","webTitle":"Society","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/society","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/society/society","referenc