 Cameron faced embarrassment this morning when he tweeted earnestly about a new cap on benefits. The <a href=\"https://twitter.com/David_Cameron/status/356670882065809408\">prime minister posted</a>: 'We're rolling out a cap on Benefits today - <a href=\"https://twitter.com/IDS_MP\">@IDS_MP</a> and I are determined to make work pay, and help the UK compete on the #GlobalRace.' Unfortunately, the Iain Duncan-Smith account <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2013/jul/15/cameron-tweets-fake-iain-duncan-smith?CMP=twt_gu\">he referenced</a> is a spoof account, which spends a lot of time mocking the government for being out of touch and heartless. Sample tweets include: </p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>A thrifty way to keep cool in this heat wave is to dab the ice from your Champagne bucket onto your forehead.</p><p>&mdash; Iain Duncan Smith MP (@IDS_MP) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/IDS_MP/statuses/356149625931038722\">July 13, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Wonderful cocktails last night. They were bitter and left a nasty taste in the mouth but just one had me laughing. Calling them 'Coal Miner'</p><p>&mdash; Iain Duncan Smith MP (@IDS_MP) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/IDS_MP/statuses/323015131619553280\">April 13, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p>David Cameron is not the first to be taken in by a spoof Twitter account. There are hundreds of them (as we speak, someone will be making a royal baby account). For the most part, spoof accounts are pretty bland, but occasionally one pops up that really nails the parody. Here are our top spoof tweeters: </p><h2><a href=\"https://twitter.com/KimKierkegaard\">@KimKierkegaard</a></h2><p>A mash-up of quotes from the Danish philosopher Søren Kierkegaard and reality TV celebrity Kim Kardashian work amazingly well. The author obviously spends a lot of time carefully putting the tweets together, and they rarely fail to crack me up. Sample tweets include: </p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Send me pics of your best Kardashian Glow tan! So that we may glimpse the damage done to your soul.&mdash; KimKierkegaardashian (@KimKierkegaard) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/KimKierkegaard/statuses/316373884930777089\">March 26, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Are passions, then, the pagans of the soul? Is reason alone baptized? The sexy secretary look lets you have both.&mdash; KimKierkegaardashian (@KimKierkegaard) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/KimKierkegaard/statuses/343231393268105216\">June 8, 2013</a></p></blockquote><h2><a href=\"https://twitter.com/DoritosOntario\">@DoritosOntario</a></h2><p>Most corporate accounts are boring, official and unimaginative (don't you dare say that about <a href=\"https://twitter.com/commentisfree\">@commentisfree</a>). So we welcome this parody account for Doritos in Canada. Might even make us buy their dusty orange crisps. Sample tweets include:</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Don't worry about the shape of Doritos similarity to illuminati symbology. Just don't worry about it. What's on TV?&mdash; Doritos Ontario (@DoritosOntario) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DoritosOntario/statuses/355381313701818368\">July 11, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Do you feed your pets Doritos? Send us a photo, but please dont tell the police we told you to feed your pet Doritos. But pls take a picture</p><p>&mdash; Doritos Ontario (@DoritosOntario) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DoritosOntario/statuses/353349814458654720\">July 6, 2013</a></p></blockquote><h2><a href=\"https://twitter.com/FakeAPStylebook\">@FakeAPStylebook</a><br /></h2><p>Respected writers might use the AP stylebook to guide them on grammar and punctuation, but the smart people go straight to FakeAPStylebook. Likely to enrage purists, this account offers terrible advice for aspiring authors, but it's very funny. Sample tweets include:</p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>If you wrote a column making a hilariously incorrect election prediction, an apology or resignat--ha ha just kidding, it's cool.&mdash; Fake AP Stylebook (@FakeAPStylebook) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/FakeAPStylebook/statuses/268444518976729088\">November 13, 2012</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Baning - Using a Sean Connery impression to scare people. Don't confuse with \"boning,\" something else Sean Connery does better than you.&mdash; Fake AP Stylebook (@FakeAPStylebook) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/FakeAPStylebook/statuses/228866832277327873\">July 27, 2012</a></p></blockquote><h2><a href=\"https://twitter.com/MrsStephenFry\">@MrsStephenFry</a></h2><p>One of the original parody accounts, Mrs Fry pertains to be the long suffering wife of Stephen Fry, who helped boost her popularity by playing along. Since her early success, she's written a book, and come out of the shadows a little bit. Sample tweets include: </p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Our kids are so embarrassed when there's sex on tv they go straight to bed. Stephen and I sometimes fall off but it's worth it. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23bedtimelive&amp;src=hash\">#bedtimelive</a>&mdash; Mrs Stephen Fry (@MrsStephenFry) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/MrsStephenFry/statuses/314113184363589632\">March 19, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Please give anything you can to Comic Relief and hopefully, together, we can help put Michael McIntyre out of his misery. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23RND&amp;src=hash\">#RND</a>&mdash; Mrs Stephen Fry (@MrsStephenFry) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/MrsStephenFry/statuses/312669149593751552\">March 15, 2013</a></p></blockquote><h2><a href=\"https://twitter.com/DMReporter\">@DMReporter</a></h2><p>Exactly what it sounds like. This parody account has adopted the voice of the Daily Mail to an almost spooky level of accuracy. Mainly tweeting about cancer, women and what you should be outraged by, this account is like reading the real Daily Mail, but with added laughs. Sample tweets include: </p><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>This week's Daily Mail Cancer List: &#10;Mo) Shadows &#10;Tu) Lidl &#10;We) Hayfever &#10;Th) German food &#10;Fr) Sun lotion &#10;Sa) Pylons &#10;Su) Stopped clocks&mdash; The DM Reporter (@DMReporter) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DMReporter/statuses/356369358555062272\">July 14, 2013</a></p></blockquote><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>APPEAL: Are you a freelance journalist and mother? Will you write an article personally critical of your children? Contact our newsdesk now.</p><p>&mdash; The DM Reporter (@DMReporter) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DMReporter/statuses/355301854357360640\">July 11, 2013</a></p></blockquote><p> Do you have a favourite spoof Twitter account? Let us know in the comments below.</p>","headline":"Top 5 spoof Twitter accounts","trailText":"<p><strong>Bella Mackie: Open thread:</strong> It's easily done - David Cameron got taken in by a parody IDS Twitter account. Here's five of our favourites. Tell us yours</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/7/15/1373878699450/5afd7196-405d-44d8-87c2-db58c0d04f86-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"702","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"412848960","allowUgc":"false","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Bella Mackie","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-07-15T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1936713","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-07-18T11:32:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/15/twitter-david-cameron-5-parody-accounts","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/15/twitter-david-cameron-5-parody-accounts","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/series/openthread","webTitle":"Open thread","description":"You asked for open threads. Here they are","type":"series"