24688/shopping-trolley-005.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3h873","standfirst":"Office for National Statistics figures find inequality has fallen in 2011-12, but coalition's benefit curbs may also reverse trend","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-05-22T00:21:00Z","body":"<p>Post-recession Britain has become a less unequal place than at any time for 25 years, with wages stagnating while benefits and tax credits have helped protect the incomes of the poorest, <a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171778_317365.pdf\" title=\"\">according to official figures</a>.</p><p>In its annual analysis of the impact of taxes and benefits on consumers, the Office for National Statistics said that in 2011-12 the gap between rich and poor was at its narrowest since 1986, measured using the internationally recognised Gini index. The index places countries on a scale between perfect equality, where everyone's income is the same – represented as a score of zero – and 100% inequality, where one person takes home the entire national income.</p><p>The measure for the UK slipped to 32.3%, from 33.7% a year earlier. In the US, the Gini index is above 40%, while in Sweden, for example, it is as low as 25%.</p><p>Inequality tends to fall during economic downturns, as benefits are uprated in line with inflation while wages are hit by rising unemployment. But experts expect the recent decline in inequality to be reversed, once the coalition government's benefit curbs come into force.</p><p>Robert Joyce, senior economist at the Institute for Fiscal Studies, said: \"For low-income households, much of the pain is happening now or is still to come, because we're in the middle of a period when benefits are being cut back.\"</p><p>Average annual wages fell by more than £1,200 in the three years following the crash, while pensions and most state benefits continued to be uprated in line with inflation. The average income for the poorest fifth of households was up by 6.9% over the same period. More recent policies, including the chancellor's 1% cap on working-age benefit increases until 2016, are expected to reverse that trend.</p><p>Before taxes and benefits, the richest fifth of households had an average income of £78,300 in 2011-12. That was 14 times greater than the poorest fifth, whose incomes averaged £5,400.</p><p>However, once cash benefits such as the state pension and tax credits were factored in, the ratio dropped to 6:1, with the top fifth earning £80,700 a year compared with the poorest fifth's £12,900 average. The gap was down from the previous year, when the richer fifth earned 16 times the income of the poorest households.</p><p>The ONS analysis also revealed the hefty chunk the exchequer takes from those at the bottom of the income scale in taxes. The poorest fifth of UK households lost almost a third of their disposable incomes in indirect taxes such as VAT, alcohol and fuel duty in 2011-12. The ONS said the increase in the rate of VAT from 17.5% to 20% in January 2011 helped drive the amount of indirect tax paid by the lowest earners up to £3,400 a year, or 29% of their disposable cash.</p><p>In contrast, while the richest fifth of households paid an average of £8,700, the difference in their earnings meant this was just 14% of their disposable income. \"Indirect taxes act to increase inequality of income,\" the ONS said.</p><p>Unions said the figures showed the government should prioritise lowering the rate of VAT rather than increasing the personal income tax allowance to £10,000, a pledge made by the Liberal Democrat leader, Nick Clegg.</p><p>The TUC's general secretary, Frances O'Grady, said: \"Low-income families will gain virtually nothing from the increase in the personal allowance, but will continue to lose significantly from the rise in VAT.</p><p>\"Contrary to what ministers claim, the government's tax policies are having a negative impact on the poorest households.\"</p><p>Direct taxes, including income tax, cost households an average of £7,400 over the year, equivalent to 20% of their gross income. The poorest fifth paid around £1,300 or 10% of income, of which the largest component was council tax. The richest fifth of households paid £19,900 or 25% of gross income, of which most was income tax.</p><p>The ONS said the average disposable income of a UK household was 2.24 times higher in real terms than in 1977, but that incomes had not grown evenly. While the average income of the richest households was 2.49 times higher, among the poorest households that figure fell to 1.93.</p>","headline":"UK income gap shrinks to narrowest margin for 25 years","trailText":"Office for National Statistics figures find inequality has fallen in 2011-12, but coalition's benefit curbs may also reverse trend","newspaperPageNumber":"24","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/7/10/1373482724688/shopping-trolley-005.jpg","wordcount":"680","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"412578074","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"7823313","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Heather Stewart and Hilary Osborne","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-07-11T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1934958","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-07-13T19:15:59Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/jul/10/income-gap-narrowest-margin-25-years","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/2013/jul/10/income-gap-narrowest-margin-25-years","tags":[{"id":"uk/office-for-national-statistics","webTitle":"Office for National Statistics","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/office-for-national-statistics","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk/office-for-national-statistics","references":[]},{"id":"uk/uk","webTitle":"UK news","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"